WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.885
Welcome to your PulmoCore lesson on
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, or

2
00:00:04.885 --> 00:00:08.965
ALS, one of the most important
neuromuscular diseases you'll encounter

3
00:00:08.965 --> 00:00:10.364
as a respiratory therapist.

4
00:00:11.045 --> 00:00:16.264
ALS is a progressive neurodegenerative
disorder that affects both upper and lower motor neurons.

5
00:00:17.065 --> 00:00:20.604
As these neurons deteriorate, patients
lose voluntary muscle control,

6
00:00:20.885 --> 00:00:22.864
including the muscles responsible for
breathing.

7
00:00:23.745 --> 00:00:27.625
Unlike obstructive diseases like asthma or
COPD, the problem here

8
00:00:27.625 --> 00:00:30.065
is not airflow limitation, it's muscle
failure.

9
00:00:30.924 --> 00:00:32.145
Let's break that down.

10
00:00:32.444 --> 00:00:36.025
In ALS, the diaphragm and accessory
muscles gradually weaken.

11
00:00:36.744 --> 00:00:39.505
This leads to reduced tidal volume,
ineffective cough,

12
00:00:39.724 --> 00:00:41.264
and impaired secretion clearance.

13
00:00:41.865 --> 00:00:44.944
Over time, patients develop
hypoventilation, which

14
00:00:44.944 --> 00:00:47.365
means they cannot adequately remove carbon
dioxide.

15
00:00:47.884 --> 00:00:51.764
This results in rising PaCO2, respiratory
acidosis,

16
00:00:51.805 --> 00:00:53.465
and eventually respiratory failure.

17
00:00:54.185 --> 00:00:57.104
Early in the disease, patients may present
with subtle signs

18
00:00:57.104 --> 00:01:00.465
like dyspnea on exertion, orthopnea, or

19
00:01:00.465 --> 00:01:01.025
morning headaches.

20
00:01:01.744 --> 00:01:04.084
These are key clues of nocturnal
hypoventilation.

21
00:01:04.764 --> 00:01:07.885
As the disease progresses, you'll see
decreased vital capacity,

22
00:01:08.544 --> 00:01:11.464
weak cough, and increasing dependence on
ventilatory support.

23
00:01:12.044 --> 00:01:14.745
From a board exam perspective, remember
this.

24
00:01:15.084 --> 00:01:18.985
ALS causes respiratory failure due to
muscle weakness, not lung

25
00:01:18.985 --> 00:01:19.364
disease.

26
00:01:19.724 --> 00:01:23.345
The key is recognizing when ventilatory
support is needed, not

27
00:01:23.345 --> 00:01:24.125
just oxygen.

28
00:01:24.964 --> 00:01:27.724
As you move through this lesson, focus on
connecting muscle

29
00:01:27.724 --> 00:01:31.125
weakness to ventilation failure,
interpreting respiratory metrics,

30
00:01:31.324 --> 00:01:34.105
and making timely decisions about support
and escalation.

31
00:01:34.584 --> 00:01:38.565
Because in ALS, early recognition and
intervention can make a

32
00:01:38.565 --> 00:01:39.824
profound difference in patient outcomes.

